 a long prayer, suffused with the language of Scripture and addressed to God, not man. Augustine tells the story of his life not for its own significance but in order to discern how, as a drama of sin and salvation leading to God, it fits into sacred history. "We have to read Augustine as we do Dante," Wills writes, "alert to rich layer upon layer of Scriptural and theological symbolism." Wills also addresses the long afterlife of the book, from controversy in its own time and relative neglect during the Middle Ages to a renewed prominence beginning in the fourteenth century and persisting to today, when the Confessions has become an object of interest not just for Christians but also historians, philosophers, psychiatrists, and literary critics. With unmatched clarity and skill, Wills strips away the centuries of misunderstanding that have accumulated around Augustine's spiritual classic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aChristian saintszAlgeriazHippo (Extinct city)vBiographyxHistory and criticism. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / History.2bisacsh  aAcademic skepticism.  aAdolf von Harnack.  aAgeless Wisdom.  aAnguish.  aAsceticism.  aAstrology.  aAugustine of Hippo.  aAutobiography.  aBeing and Time.  aBible.  aBildungsroman.  aBook of Confessions.  aBook.  aCelibacy.  aChristian.  aChristianity.  aChurch Fathers.  aConfessions (Augustine).  aConsciousness.  aConsecration.  aCreation myth.  aCriticism.  aDasein.  aDonatism.  aEcclesiology.  aEdmund Husserl.  aExamination of conscience.  aExistentialism.  aExplanation.  aFacsimile.  aFalse prophet.  aForgetting.  aGervasius and Protasius.  aGifford Lectures.  aGod.  aGoethe's Faust.  aHannah Arendt.  aHedonism.  aHenri Bergson.  aHierius.  aHis Family.  aHistoricity.  aHistoriography